  "local_port": 46024,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much money do I owe my housemate?",
  "response": "Determining how much money you owe your housemate involves reviewing and calculating all shared expenses and any personal financial agreements you've established. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you determine the amount:\n\n1. **Rent:**\n   - **Total Rent:** Start by noting the total monthly rent for your residence.\n   - **Your Share:** Determine what portion of the rent you agreed to pay. This could be an equal split or based on room size, income, or another arrangement.\n   - **Calculation Example:** If the total rent is $1,200 and you agree to split it equally, you owe $600.\n\n2. **Utilities:**\n   - **List of Utilities:** Identify all shared utilities such as electricity, water, gas, internet, and cable.\n   - **Payment Method:** Agree on how to split each utility. Common methods include equal splits, percentage based on income, or usage-based splits.\n   - **Calculation Example:** If the monthly electricity bill is $150 and you split it equally, you owe $75.\n\n3. **Groceries and Household Supplies:**\n   - **Shared Expenses:** Determine if you share grocery costs or household supplies like cleaning products, toilet paper, etc.\n   - **Tracking Purchases:** Use a shared spreadsheet or app to track who buys what and how much each person should contribute.\n   - **Calculation Example:** If monthly groceries cost $400 and split equally, you owe $200.\n\n4. **Internet and Streaming Services:**\n   - **Subscriptions:** Include costs for internet, streaming services, or any other shared subscriptions.\n   - **Splitting Fees:** Decide if these are split equally or based on usage.\n   - **Calculation Example:** If internet is $60 per month, your share might be $30.\n\n5. **One-Time or Irregular Expenses:**\n   - **Furniture or Appliances:** If you've both contributed to purchasing shared items, calculate your respective shares.\n   - **Repairs or Maintenance:** Any costs for repairs or maintenance should be divided according to your agreement.\n   - **Calculation Example:** If you contributed $100 towards a new vacuum cleaner and agreed to split such costs, you owe another $50.\n\n6. **Debts or Loans:**\n   - **Personal Loans:** If you've lent money to your housemate or vice versa, include these amounts in your calculations.\n   - **Repayment Plans:** Follow any agreed-upon repayment schedules.\n\n7. **Miscellaneous Expenses:**\n   - **Unexpected Costs:** Factor in any other shared expenses that may arise, such as parking fees or security deposits.\n\n8. **Review Agreements:**\n   - **Written Agreement:** If you have a written agreement outlining financial responsibilities, refer to it to ensure accuracy.\n   - **Verbal Agreements:** Even if agreements are verbal, it's helpful to discuss and clarify them regularly to prevent misunderstandings.\n\n9. **Use Tools for Tracking:**\n   - **Spreadsheets:** Create a shared spreadsheet to list all expenses and track contributions.\n   - **Apps:** Consider using expense-sharing apps like Splitwise, Venmo, or others to manage and calculate shared costs automatically.\n\n10. **Communicate Openly:**\n    - **Regular Check-Ins:** Have regular discussions with your housemate to review expenses and address any discrepancies.\n    - **Adjustments:** Be open to adjusting your financial arrangements as circumstances change.\n\n**Example Calculation:**\n\nLet's say your total monthly shared expenses are as follows:\n\n- **Rent:** $1,200 (your share: $600)\n- **Utilities:** $300 (your share: $150)\n- **Groceries:** $400 (your share: $200)\n- **Internet:** $60 (your share: $30)\n- **Miscellaneous:** $100 (your share: $50)\n\n**Total You Owe:**\n$600 (Rent) + $150 (Utilities) + $200 (Groceries) + $30 (Internet) + $50 (Miscellaneous) = **$1,030**\n\n**Final Tips:**\n\n- **Be Transparent:** Share all receipts and bills with your housemate to maintain transparency.\n- **Set Payment Deadlines:** Agree on when payments are due each month to ensure timely contributions.\n- **Handle Discrepancies Promptly:** If there's a disagreement or mistake, address it as soon as possible to maintain a good living relationship.\n\nBy systematically reviewing each category of shared expenses and maintaining open communication with your housemate, you can accurately determine how much money you owe and ensure that both parties are satisfied with the financial arrangement.",
